'''Eyeball network''' is a [[slang]] term used by [[Computer network|network engineers]] and architects that refers to an access network<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://drpeering.net/a/Internet-Peering-Playbook/Second-Edition/Source/HTML_IPP/chapters/ch10-6-Evolution-6-Access-Power-Peering/ch10-6-Evolution-6-Access-Power-Peering.html |title=Evolution #6 – Access Power Peering |website=DrPeering International |access-date=18 February 2017}}</ref> whose primary users use the [[Computer network|network]] to "look at things" (browse the Internet, read email, etc.) and consume content,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.akamai.com/us/en/multimedia/documents/technical-publication/the-growing-complexity-of-internet-interconnection-technical-publication.pdf |title=The Growing Complexity of Internet Interconnection |last=Faratin |first=Peyman |last2=Clark |first2=David |year=2008 |website=Akamai |publisher=Akamai Technologies |last3=Bauer |first3=Steven |last4=Lehr |first4=William |last5=Gilmore |first5=Patrick  |last6=Berger |first6=Arthur|access-date=18 February 2017}}https://www.akamai.com/us/en/multimedia/documents/technical-publication/the-growing-complexity-of-internet-interconnection-technical-publication.pdf</ref> as opposed to a network that may be used primarily to generate its own data, or "content networks".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://object.cato.org/sites/cato.org/files/serials/files/regulation/2010/2/regv33n1-6.pdf |title=Network Neutrality or Internet Innovation? |last=Yoo |first=Christopher |year=2010 |website=Cato |publisher=Cato Institute |access-date=18 February 2017}}</ref>

The term "eyeball network" is often overhead in conversations and seen in articles<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.circleid.com/posts/20140429_what_does_network_neutrality_mean/ |title=What Does "Network Neutrality" Mean? |last=Bellovin |first=Steven |website=CircleID |publisher=Iomemo Inc |access-date=18 February 2017}}</ref> that discuss peering relationships between other networks as well as [[net neutrality]] issues.

